<sn><md>#### **Core Observation**

I am 100% sure of this observation. In a world where people do not think about their parents, do you think they will care about you? Here, everyone tries to bring others down and prove their own perception. People try to fulfill their interests by giving you an offer. The offer may look enjoyable at first, but over time you will understand that they are fulfilling their interest by using you. So do not take quick actions with unknown people. If the person is known, take time and ask every possible question. If unknown, always say no.
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Incident 1

When I went to buy my desktop build from Elephant Road (technology shop), I listed every item I would buy with their model and price. Everything was good, and there was a crowd in that small shop. Three more groups had come to buy computers there, so I got a little time to inspect each part.

At the last point, when they gave me the monitor, they offered me a Gigasonic monitor with a 3-year warranty. But I wanted a HiPower 100Hz monitor. I asked them if they were the same price because I did not have enough budget. They replied yes, they were the same price. Since the price was the same, I thought the Gigasonic must also be 100Hz. But when I inspected it at night, I found that it was a 75Hz monitor priced at 7000 TK, while I paid 8100 TK for the HiPower.

Gigasonic: 75Hz, 1-year warranty, 7000 TK<br>
HiPower: 100Hz, 3-year warranty, 8100 TK

I paid for HiPower 100Hz but received Gigasonic 75Hz. My mistake was that I confirmed the price but not the quality. They quickly packed my monitor and did not give me enough time to properly check the model due to the crowd. But the next day, I sent my father to replace it, and they replaced it. My father is very patient.

Here observe their cunning offered had a interest of themselves not mine.I did not catched the point but I quickly respond to my mistook.</md></sn><sn><md>#### Related Incident

One day, my aunt asked me to buy a painkiller for her. The seller gave me another medicine and told me that it was better. I listened to him and gave that medicine to my aunt. My aunt rejected it, and I told her to take it, saying it was a better version.

But my aunt, an intelligent lady, checked the medicine details with her little daughter and found that it was an allergic medicine. I also checked later and felt ashamed that I suggested she take it without verifying the details.

Every time we try to buy something, the seller gives us something else. As they regularly deal with people, they know common loopholes and use them to trick people. We will discuss how to handle buying situations in another section.
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Incident 2

One day at 8 PM, Akondo (a university classmate) called me and invited me to play football with them the next day on the university field. I am usually not interested in football matches, but for some exercise, I agreed.

For the first 80 minutes, they did not call me to play. Only in the last 10 minutes did they call me (there may be a reason because I usually do not wear shorts; I used to wear long trousers). The match ended in a quarrel due to an offside issue.

The next day, they asked me to give them 120 TK. I did not understand why, since I only played one match for just 10 minutes. I told them I would pay, but I will not. Here, they had no mistake, but this shows a kind of observation where offers come with hidden interest.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Incident 3

My uncle, Anis Mollick, offered my father an opportunity to buy a piece of land where they could build shops and rent them out in the future. Based on this proposal, they took 40,000 TK from my father.

However, later they registered the property in their own name and returned the 40,000 TK after a few months. In effect, they used my father's money when they needed it and then returned it once their purpose was fulfilled.

Please observe the situation carefully. Here, one brother acted against the interest of another brother. If even close family members can prioritize their own interests, then it is important to be cautious whenever anyone presents an offer. What appears to be an opportunity may sometimes be a plan designed primarily to serve the other person's interests rather than your own.

The lesson I took from this incident is that every offer should be examined carefully, regardless of who makes it. Trust should not replace verification. 😈
</md></sn><sn><md>### Rules to Handle Offers {.text-center}

Offers are usually presented in an enjoyable and attractive way, so do not be tricked by excitement or greed. Always follow the 50:50 rule. When someone gives you an offer:

* If it is not important, reject it as quickly as possible.Prefer important over interest in a offer.
* If you are interested, make sure it comes from a known person. However, remember that the offer may still serve their own interests.

  * Take time to think about the offer and tell them that you are busy and will inform them later.
  * Analyze the offer carefully and seek advice from experts or elders.
  * Ask every possible question and verify the answers.
  * Apply the 50:50 rule to ensure the offer is realistic. If you give 100 TK, do not expect to receive a product worth 1000 TK.
  * Inspect and verify the product, service, or opportunity before accepting it.
  * Hope we win.

